-- 2012-05-04T22:02:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-05-04/oil-natural-gas-increase-as-grains-drop-commodities-at.html
The Standard & Poor’s GSCI  gauge  of 24
commodities declined 2.4 percent to 653.60. The UBS Bloomberg
CMCI  index  of 26 raw materials dropped 1.1 percent to 1,539.116
at 4:59 p.m. in  New York .  CRUDE OIL  Oil fell below $100 a barrel for the first time since
February as U.S. employers added fewer workers than forecast,
stoking concern that demand won’t be enough to reduce
inventories from their highest level in 21 years.  Crude oil for June delivery tumbled $4.05 to $98.49 a
barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange , the lowest
settlement since Feb. 7. It was the biggest one-day drop since
Dec. 14 and capped a 6.1 percent decline for the week, the most  Brent oil for June settlement fell $2.90, or 2.5 percent,
to end the session at $113.18 a barrel on the London-based ICE
Futures Europe exchange. It was the lowest close since Feb. 2.  OIL PRODUCTS  Gasoline slid below $3 a gallon for the first time since
February as slower-than-estimated U.S. job growth and signs of
contraction in  Europe  raised concern that global fuel demand
will decline.  Gasoline for June delivery declined 7.42 cents, or 2.4
percent, to settle at $2.9758 a gallon on the Nymex, the lowest
settlement since Feb. 10. Gasoline fell 7.2 percent this week,
the biggest weekly loss since September. The futures dropped 6.1
percent in April  June-delivery heating oil fell 7.81 cents, or 2.5 percent,
to settle at $3.0088 a gallon on the exchange, a 15-week low.
Prices lost 5.4 percent this week, the largest weekly retreat
since Sept. 23.  GRAINS  Corn rose for a second day on signs that U.S. farmers
limited sales from inventories as they spent more time in the
field planting this year’s crop. Soybeans gained for the first
time in four days, and wheat fell.  Corn futures for July delivery advanced 0.9 percent to
close at $6.2025 a bushel at 1:15 p.m. on the  Chicago  Board of
Trade, paring this week’s decline to 0.8 percent. Prices are
down 3.7 percent since the government said March 30 that U.S.
farmers this year will plant the most acres since 1937.  Soybean futures for July delivery gained 0.3 percent to
$14.7825 a bushel on the CBOT, paring the weekly drop to 1
percent. On May 2, the commodity touched $15.125, the highest
since July 2008.  Wheat futures for July delivery slumped 1 percent to $6.095
a bushel on the CBOT. Prices dropped 6.2 percent for the week,
the biggest decline since September, after rains and warm
weather boosted U.S. yield potential.  LIVESTOCK  Hog futures dropped to the lowest this year as U.S. meat
demand is slowing amid signs of weak economic growth. Cattle
also fell.  Hog futures for June settlement slumped 1.4 percent to
settle at 83.725 cents a pound at 1 p.m. on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange. Earlier, the commodity reached 83.025, the
lowest since Dec. 16. Prices dropped 3.3 percent this week, the
fourth straight decline. Department of Agriculture data show.  Cattle futures for June delivery fell 0.4 percent to settle
at $1.15375 a pound on the CME. The price had dropped 5 percent
this year.  Feeder-cattle futures for August settlement rose 0.6
percent to settle at $1.581 a pound in Chicago. After the close
of regular trading, the price reached $1.58275, the highest
since March 15.  NATURAL GAS  Natural gas fell for the second time in three days after a
government report on jobs signaled a slowing U.S. economy,
curbing fuel demand from factories and power plants.  Gas for June delivery declined 6.1 cents to settle at
$2.279 per million British thermal units on the Nymex. Gas rose
4.3 percent this week, marking the first time prices have risen
for two consecutive weeks since the period ended Dec. 2.  SOFT COMMODITIES  Sugar climbed the most in a week after the European Union
said that it plans to import the sweetener and on concern that
rains may disrupt supplies in  Brazil , the world’s biggest
producer. Coffee and cocoa declined.  Raw sugar for July delivery advanced 0.8 percent to settle
at 20.81 cents a pound at 1:58 p.m. on ICE Futures U.S. in New
York, the largest increase for a most-active contract since
April 25. The price is still down 1.9 percent this week.  Arabica-coffee futures for July delivery fell 0.7 percent
to $1.746 a pound on ICE. Cocoa futures for July delivery
slipped 0.8 percent to $2,289 a ton.  In London futures trading, refined sugar and robusta coffee
rose, while cocoa dropped on NYSE Liffe. London commodity
trading will be closed May 7 for a public holiday in the U.K.  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold rose for the first time in a week after a government
report showed U.S. employers added fewer workers than forecast
in April, raising speculation that the  Federal Reserve  will
boost stimulus measures to spur growth.  Gold futures for June delivery gained 0.6 percent to settle
at $1,645.20 an ounce at 1:42 p.m. on the Comex in New York.
Today’s increase paired the metal’s weekly decline to 1.2
percent.  Silver futures for July delivery gained 1.4 percent to
$30.432 an ounce on the Comex.  On the Nymex, palladium futures for June delivery fell 1.4
percent to $652.15 an ounce. Earlier, prices retreated to
$649.50, the lowest since April 17. Platinum futures for July
delivery rose 0.2 percent to $1,536 an ounce on the Nymex,
rising for the first time in three days.  BASE METALS  Copper dropped for a third straight day in New York after a
report showed the U.S. added fewer jobs in April than economists
expected, adding to evidence that economic growth is slowing and
demand for the metal may slow.  Copper futures for July delivery slid 0.4 percent to settle
at $3.721 a pound at 1:17 p.m. on the Comex in New York. Prices
fell 2.7 percent this week. The most-active contract has gained
8.3 percent in 2012.  On the  London  Metal Exchange, copper for delivery in three
months dropped 0.7 percent to $8,175 a ton ($3.71 a pound).
Nickel, zinc and lead gained in London, while aluminum and tin
slumped. The LME will be closed May 7 for a U.K. public holiday.  Nickel was up 1.7 percent at $17,575 a ton in London.  Aluminum, tin, zinc and lead dropped in London.  To contact the reporter on this story:
